"# Chapter 12 — Sound and motion on one timeline

Most languages treat sound and animation as separate systems. You call one library to play a note and another library to move a sprite; if you want them synchronized, you build the coordination yourself with wall-clock queries and math.

Motoi ships with sound and motion on the *same* timeline. When you say `(audio/tempo 128)` and `(animation/tick dt)`, both systems agree about what time it is and what a beat costs. A drum hit and a sprite bounce that should land together can be declared together and land together.

This is a small idea with a large payoff. It is one of the things Motoi does better than most languages, because most languages inherited their audio API from a C wrapper and their animation API from a browser or game engine, and the two were never designed to know about each other.

## 12.1 The timeline

Motoi's core timing is a single monotonic clock, ticked at whatever cadence the host provides (typically ~60 fps for graphics, sample-accurate for audio). Two subsystems read from that clock:

- **Audio scheduling.** `audio/play`, `note/strike`, `note/place-at`, `synth/kit`, `synth/chord`. These schedule events *relative* to the current tempo and cursor.
- **Animation tweening.** `motion`, `motion/move-to`, `fade`, `slide`, `bounce`. These interpolate values over a duration in seconds.

Because both reference the same clock, cross-domain synchronization is a natural consequence.

## 12.2 Tempo as a first-class value

Set the tempo once. Everything else derives:

```scheme
(audio/tempo 128)     ; 128 bpm — dance music
```

Verified:

```
$ bin/motoi eval '(audio/tempo 128)'
128
```

Every audio verb that takes a duration takes it in *seconds*. At 128 bpm, a beat is 60/128 = 0.469 seconds. A quarter beat (a sixteenth note) is ~0.117 seconds. You can compute this once and reuse:

```scheme
(define bpm 128)
(define beat (/ 60 bpm))
(define eighth (/ beat 2))
(define sixteenth (/ beat 4))

(audio/play 'tone 440 sixteenth)
```

Verified:

```
$ bin/motoi eval '(define bpm 128) (define beat (/ 60 bpm)) (define eighth (/ beat 2)) eighth'
0.234375
```

If you want a metric-aware audio system where you play *at beat 3.5* rather than *0.72 seconds from now*, wrap the tempo:

```scheme
(define (at-beat n)
  (* n (/ 60 (audio/tempo))))

(note/place-at 'C4 (at-beat 0.5) 'quarter)
(note/place-at 'E4 (at-beat 1.0) 'quarter)
(note/place-at 'G4 (at-beat 1.5) 'quarter)
```

`note/place-at` is one of Motoi's most useful verbs: schedule a note at an absolute time offset from now. The audio engine keeps a scheduled timeline; ticks advance it.

## 12.3 The animation timeline

Motion primitives return tween handles. The animation engine holds them and calls `animation/tick` to advance them each frame:

```scheme
(motion 'up 3)                     ; move something up 3 units
(fade 'in 1.0)                     ; fade in over 1 second
(slide 'left 0.5)                  ; slide left over 0.5 seconds
(bounce 3 1.0)                     ; bounce 3 times over 1 second
```

Verified — the tween handles are opaque:

```
$ bin/motoi eval '(fade (quote in) 1.0)'
[object Object]
```

The animation engine tracks them internally. On each frame:

```scheme
(animation/tick (/ 1 60))   ; 60 fps
```

Verified:

```
$ bin/motoi eval '(animation/tick 0.016)'
0
```

Returns the count of tweens still running (0 here because nothing was actually queued in a fresh eval). In a real game loop, you'd tick every frame with the frame delta.

## 12.4 The crux — a beat and a bounce that land together

Say you want a sprite to bounce on every kick drum hit. In most languages you'd:

1. Schedule the drum hit.
2. Query the wall clock at some point.
3. Compute when the bounce should start.
4. Start the bounce.
5. Hope the audio latency doesn't push things out of sync.

In Motoi, both subsystems read the same clock. If you declare them together, they run together:

```scheme
(define (kick-and-bounce sprite)
  (synth/kit 'kick 0.15)
  (bounce sprite 1 0.15))
```

Called once, both happen now. The kick will play for 150 ms; the bounce animates over the same 150 ms. Their timing is aligned because they share the clock. There is no coordination code because there is no coordination *needed*.

Extending to a beat pattern:

```scheme
(define (loop-beat sprite n)
  (let go ((i 0))
    (when (< i n)
      (kick-and-bounce sprite)
      ;; wait until next beat (audio-scheduler handles this)
      (go (+ i 1)))))
```

The audio scheduler queues each kick sample-accurately; the animation engine schedules each bounce; both happen on their shared timeline.

## 12.5 A chord and a fade that end together

The other direction: an animation triggers when a sound completes.

```scheme
(define (chord-then-fade)
  (synth/chord (list 440 550 660) 2.0)   ; two-second chord
  (motion/on-settle
    (fade 'out 2.0)                      ; two-second fade
    (lambda () (display \"scene ended\"))))
```

`motion/on-settle` fires a callback when the tween completes. Since the fade is 2 seconds and the chord is 2 seconds, they finish together, and the callback fires. Cross-subsystem completion synchronization.

## 12.6 Notes and pitches

Motoi's audio kit has both raw-Hz and named-pitch APIs. Named pitches:

```scheme
(note/strike 'C4 0.25)         ; middle C for a quarter second
(note/strike 'A440 0.25)       ; standard tuning A
(note/strike 'D#5 0.125)       ; D-sharp octave 5, eighth-second
```

Under the hood, these convert to Hz via a lookup table. The names follow scientific pitch notation.

Chords with named notes:

```scheme
(synth/chord (list 'C4 'E4 'G4) 1.0)     ; C major triad
```

## 12.7 Kits and patches

`synth/kit` gives you drum sounds by name:

```scheme
(synth/kit 'kick 0.15)
(synth/kit 'snare 0.15)
(synth/kit 'hat 0.05)
(synth/kit 'tom-hi 0.2)
(synth/kit 'tom-lo 0.2)
(synth/kit 'clap 0.1)
```

Verified — kick plays:

```
$ bin/motoi eval \"(synth/kit 'kick 0.2)\"
ok
```

`synth/play` gives you a raw pitched patch:

```scheme
(synth/play 440 0.25)          ; 440 Hz for 250 ms
```

For the demo-scene work in Chapter 16 you'll layer these into full beats.

## 12.8 Envelopes and shapes

Sounds have shapes over time — attack, sustain, decay, release (ADSR). Motoi's `audio/play` takes a shape parameter:

```scheme
;; 'tone kind — square wave (chiptune default)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.25 'square)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.25 'sine)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.25 'saw)
(audio/play 'tone 440 0.25 'noise)
```

Each shape has a characteristic feel:

- **Square:** rich in odd harmonics; the classic 8-bit sound.
- **Sine:** pure, mellow; used sparingly, felt everywhere.
- **Saw:** aggressive, buzzy; leads and basses.
- **Noise:** unpitched; drums, effects, textures.

Chapter 16 explores composing these into a chip-tune palette.

## 12.9 A minimal sequencer

A sequencer is a data-driven beat player. The audio kit gives you the primitives; the language gives you the composition. A 4-bar sequencer:

```scheme
(define pattern
  (list
    (list 'kick 'rest 'snare 'rest)
    (list 'kick 'kick 'snare 'rest)
    (list 'kick 'rest 'snare 'kick)
    (list 'kick 'rest 'snare 'snare)))

(define (play-bar bar step-time)
  (for-each
    (lambda (hit)
      (unless (eq? hit 'rest)
        (synth/kit hit step-time))
      ;; audio scheduler advances by step-time regardless
      )
    bar))

(define (play-pattern pat)
  (define step-time (/ 60 (audio/tempo) 4))     ; sixteenth note
  (for-each (lambda (bar) (play-bar bar step-time)) pat))

(play-pattern pattern)
```

This reads like sheet music. The macro form of the beat DSL (Chapter 11) makes it read cleaner still.

## 12.10 A note-and-move dance

Here's the payoff pattern — sound and motion woven together:

```scheme
(define (dance-step sprite pitch)
  (note/strike pitch 0.25)
  (bounce sprite 1 0.25))

(define (dance sprite melody)
  (for-each
    (lambda (note)
      (dance-step sprite note))
    melody))

(dance my-sprite (list 'C4 'D4 'E4 'F4 'G4 'A4 'B4 'C5))
```

Each note plays; each note the sprite bounces once; scale ascends; sprite bounces eight times. Sound and motion share the tempo, share the timeline, share the intent.

## 12.11 The macro payoff

Now combine Chapter 11 with this. A macro for beat-plus-motion:

```scheme
(define-syntax on-beat
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_ (sound motion) ...)
     (begin
       (begin sound motion)
       ...))))

;; usage
(on-beat
  ((synth/kit 'kick 0.15)  (bounce ball 1 0.15))
  ((synth/kit 'snare 0.15) (fade ball 'flash 0.15))
  ((synth/kit 'kick 0.15)  (bounce ball 1 0.15))
  ((synth/kit 'snare 0.15) (slide ball 'right 0.15)))
```

The macro is trivial. What it *reads like* is a score: each row is a beat, with sound and visual side-by-side.

You could not do this cleanly in a language where sound and motion live in different libraries with different time bases. In Motoi you can.

## 12.12 Comparisons

**In Python**, sound is `pygame.mixer` or `simpleaudio`; animation is `pygame.sprite` or Pyglet; syncing them requires wall-clock queries and manual scheduling. Doable, but you're the coordinator.

**In JavaScript**, `Web Audio API` gives you sample-accurate scheduling with `AudioContext.currentTime`; canvas animation uses `requestAnimationFrame`; they run on the *same* clock in the browser but the APIs are unrelated shapes. Sync is possible; convenient it isn't.

**In Godot / Unity**, sound and animation live inside the engine and coordinate via engine primitives. This is comparable to Motoi's model, at the cost of a much bigger runtime.

Motoi's win: same expressive model, tiny footprint, s-expression composition. If you want to hand a kid a computer and have them make a beat with matching visuals in one afternoon, this is the story that works.

## 12.13 Latency, sample accuracy, and the honest caveats

Motoi's audio scheduler queues events. Actual playback latency depends on the host — a browser Web Audio backend, a Node.js audio backend, a native backend. Sample-accurate scheduling is *possible* through the underlying engine but is not guaranteed at the Motoi API level. For most work — games, demos, teaching — it's imperceptibly good. For professional DAW work where every millisecond matters, use a DAW.

Animation is frame-rate-limited to whatever the host provides. `animation/tick` takes a delta; you supply it. On a 60 fps host, you get 16.67 ms resolution.

These are honest boundaries. Motoi is a chip-tune-and-demo-scene tool, not a Pro Tools competitor. It is *very good* at the thing it aims at.

## 12.14 What to remember

- One clock, two subsystems.
- Tempo is first-class; every audio duration reads from it.
- Motion tweens run on the same tick as audio schedules.
- `motion/on-settle` fires callbacks at tween completion — cross-subsystem synchronization.
- Named pitches, drum kits, shape parameters — all present in the base.
- Macros let you write beat-plus-motion scores that read like music.
- Not a DAW replacement; a fantasy-console-scale audio+visual kit.

Next chapter: Cortex — programs that remember what you did.
")
